==English==
===Etymology===
From New Latin '''[[fricativus]]''', from Latin '''[[fricatus]]''' (past participle of '''[[fricare]]''', ''to rub'') + adjective suffix [[-ivus]].

===Noun===
#(''phonetics'') Any of several [[sound]]s produced by air flowing through a constriction in the oral cavity and typically producing a [[sibilant]], [[hissing]], or [[buzzing]] quality; a fricative [[consonant]]. English F and S are fricatives.

====Translations====
*Japanese: [[摩擦音]] (masatsuon)
*Russian: [[фрикативный]] (frikativnyj) ''m''

===Synonyms===
*[[spirant]]

===Adjective===
#(''phonetics'') produced by air flowing through a restriction in the oral cavity.

===Derivatives===
*fricativise (''Intransitive verb'') to become a fricative.
*fricativisation (''noun'') The process whereby a sound becomes a fricative.

